{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568801"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.31,0.58,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14261"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89313"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"12300"},{"type":"tags","id":"12301"},{"type":"tags","id":"12302"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, productive cough with yellow sputum, and progressive shortness of breath. She is 12 weeks pregnant with her first child and has had an uncomplicated pregnancy thus far. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications apart from pregnancy vitamins. She works as a primary school teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals crackles in the right lower zone. Heart sounds are normal. The fetal heart rate is 150/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show a white cell count of 15.0 \u00d7 10^9/L (4.0-11.0) with neutrophilia and C-reactive protein of 120 mg/L (\u0026lt;5). The patient expresses concern about having a chest X-ray due to potential radiation effects on her developing baby.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding imaging for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest ultrasound instead of chest X-ray","Low-dose chest CT scan","Empiric antibiotics without imaging","Proceed with chest X-ray with appropriate shielding","MRI of the chest"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of community-acquired pneumonia during pregnancy, including fever, productive cough, dyspnoea, and focal chest findings. The elevated white cell count with neutrophilia and C-reactive protein further support this diagnosis. Pneumonia during pregnancy is associated with increased maternal and fetal morbidity, making prompt diagnosis and treatment essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with chest X-ray with appropriate shielding\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. A standard two-view chest X-ray delivers less than 0.01 mGy of radiation to the fetus, which is a tiny fraction of the 50 mGy (5 rad) threshold considered potentially harmful. With appropriate abdominal shielding, this exposure is further reduced. The patient should be reassured that the benefits of accurate diagnosis far outweigh the minimal radiation risk. Delaying diagnosis of pneumonia poses a far greater risk to both mother and fetus than the minimal radiation from a chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of chest X-ray is also essential in assessing for pneumonia severity looking for multi-lobar involvement and complications such as effusion. In visualisation of pneumonia, this also assists in reducing likelihood of alternative diagnoses such as pulmonary embolism, which should also be a consideration in pregnant patients with dyspnoea, tachycardia and hypoxia due to their hypercoagulable state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric antibiotics without imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is not the optimal approach. While antibiotics will likely be started promptly, confirming the diagnosis with imaging is important, as well as the assessment of severity of pneumonia to assist in treatment guidance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E has emerging utility in diagnosing pneumonia but has limitations in visualizing certain lung regions and is highly operator-dependent. It is not yet considered a first-line diagnostic tool for pneumonia in most clinical settings, particularly when standard chest X-ray is readily available and safe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-dose chest CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E would deliver significantly more radiation than a chest X-ray (approximately 0.1-0.4 mGy to the fetus) and is unnecessary for the initial evaluation of suspected uncomplicated pneumonia. CT would be considered if there were concerns about complications or if the diagnosis remained unclear after initial assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E does not involve ionizing radiation and is safe in pregnancy. However, it is not routinely used for diagnosing pneumonia due to limited availability, higher cost, longer acquisition times, and lower sensitivity for detecting air-space disease compared to X-ray. MRI would be considered in specific situations where radiation must be absolutely avoided and the diagnosis cannot be made by other means.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, when pneumonia is suspected during pregnancy, a chest X-ray should not be withheld due to unfounded radiation concerns. The benefits of prompt diagnosis and appropriate treatment far outweigh the minimal risk from radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest X-rays are safe during pregnancy with fetal radiation exposure of less than 0.01 mGy, well below the 50 mGy (5 rad) threshold for concern.","Clinically indicated chest X-rays should never be withheld during pregnancy when pneumonia is suspected.","Pneumonia in pregnancy is associated with increased maternal and fetal morbidity, making prompt diagnosis essential."],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89313"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89313"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-23T09:21:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-23T13:51:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14261"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations